n) are either promoted and upheld as “Canadian” bodies while others are marginalized in or excluded from media representations. Essays are grouped into three sections: Embodied Ideals, The Embodiment of “Others,” and Embodied Activism and Advocacy. Written in an accessible style for a broad audience of scholars and students, this volume is original within the field of visual media, affect theory, and embodiment due to its emphasis on detailed empirical and, in some cases, ethnographic research within a Canadian context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMass media and culturezCanada. 0aMass media and nationalismzCanada. 0aNational characteristics in mass media. 0aNational characteristics, Canadian. 4aCultural Studies. 4aFilm & Media. 4aSocial Science: Gender Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aCanadian identity.  aCommunity art.  aFigure skating.  aGender identity.  aHockey.  aMedia.  aMind/body dualism.  aOlympics.1 aCraig, Ailsa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGauthier, Jennifer L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHogeveen, Bryan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackman, Michael Connors, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMannik, Lynda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMannik, Lynda, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcGarry, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcGarry, Karen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMitchinson, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichardson, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpencer, Dale, econt